=======
bedrock
=======

A playbook of the architectural root of my security model. It defines the foundational layers, principles and controls that every system must satisfy before it can be considered trusted.

==========================
The Defense-in-Depth Model
==========================

Security is engineered sequentially from the system's lowest trust boundary outward to my digital identity. If a lower layer is compromised, the structural integrity of every layer above it is void.

[ Layer 5: Alias ] --- Identity
    [ Layer 4: Credentials ] --- Password Manager, TOTP
        [ Layer 3: Gateway ] --- Browser, Search Engine
            [ Layer 2: Network ] --- Firewall, DNS
                [ Layer 1: Compute ] --- Operating System
                    [ Layer 0: Core ] --- Firmware, Bootloader

{Didn't refer properties that are outside my scope (properties that requires external access such as routers)}

=============
Layer 0: Core
=============

The Core layer represents the lowest trust boundary of a system. It's the first code executed when the machine powers on, it consists of the firmware, the software responsible for initializing hardware and the bootloader which is responsible to execute the operating system. If this layer is compromised, no software control above it can be trusted.

Components
----------

> - Firmware
> - Bootloader

Principles
----------

> - Ensure only trusted code executes during system startup
> - Prevent unauthorized firmware modification
> - Maintain firmware integrity
> - Minimize exposure to known firmware vulnerabilities

Controls
--------

> - Keep firmware up to date
> - Enable Secure Boot
> - Lock firmware settings (with a unique password)
> - Disable booting from external media (boot order set to internal drive only)

{All controls depend on firmware password, if a password is not set, external physical access is game over}

